      "lineNbr": 88,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-07T02:41:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "argparse does have APIs for defining conflicting options, but that\u0027s not really the crux of the issue here -- throwing uncaught exceptions is.\n\nthrowing SystemExit addresses the raw traceback, but it\u0027s a really unnatural way of just calling sys.exit().  and still isn\u0027t the standard for handling CLI\u0027s.\n\nparser.error() is the clean standard way for communicating to the user \"there\u0027s a problem with your arguments\".  it should be used, not ad-hoc error display (print/sys.exit/SystemExit/whatever), and not ad-hoc re-implementation of it like you\u0027ve done here with this try+except block.\n\nwhat is the problem with just using parser.error() like every other python tool utilizing argparse ?",
      "parentUuid": "20fceaf9_4f73bab3",
      "revId": "5fa2bad2ce87ef0b880edf07e04c34fbcb7f26c4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889"
    },
